Making Sense of Al Mohler and His Nonsense

For those unaware, Southern Seminary president Al Mohler was recently seated at a panel hosted by the Kenwood Institute. The topics covered contentious issues in SBC life, including the abuse and financial crises, along with the issue of women serving in ministry and how it relates to the proposed Law Amendment.

When asked by discussion moderators and CBMW members Colin Smothers and Denny Burk about the role of women pastors in SBC churches, Mohler would suggest, The idea that you would have the word pastor applied to a woman in the Southern Baptist Conventionto the vast majority of Southern Baptists, I don't think has ever made sense.

This framing is disingenuous. 

Perhaps the issue here is that what does not make sense to white males in the seat of denominational power with ties to an institution founded upon slave-holding theology makes perfect sense to minorities. 

What does not make sense to men who refuse to see the Bibles ringing endorsement of women using their gifts in the church under the leadership and watchful care and protection of their senior pastor makes perfect sense to those who know what it is to be denied a role in the life of the church because of something they cannot control, regardless if it is skin color or gender.

What does not make sense to the majority to which Mohler claims to belong seems to make perfect sense to countless Southern Baptist pastors, professors, and minorities, including Asian and African Americans.

After the disfellowshipping of Rick Warren and Saddleback, the National African American Fellowship, SBC (NAAF) penned a letter to SBC President Bart Barber outlining the widespread concern many predominantly African American churches in SBC life have with this new threat of creedalism and autonomy infringement. This letter was not coming from the fringe of SBC life, either, as NAAF has nearly 4,000 churches and its letter outlining concerns with the Law Amendment was endorsed by former SBC President J.D. Greear.

Many of the 4,000 churches affiliated with NAAF unashamedly hold to the conservative, BFM-compatible, and biblical opinion that women may be freed up to serve in the local church in shepherding ministries under the authority of a male senior pastor who has been duly credentialed, called, and installed by the congregation. This female-empowering, congregational, and softly complementarian position has persisted in SBC life without controversy until recently.

Would Al Mohler dare suggest the positions of the pastors of these 4,000 churches dont make sense? It is likely he would not, but that did not stop him from taking a cheap shot from the insular, predominantly male, White, and Calvinist fortress that is Southern Seminary.

But African Americans are not the only group profoundly affected by the threat of creedalism and autonomy infringement. Other minority groups in SBC life have vested interests in these debates.

The Chinese Baptist Fellowship (CBF) put out an open letter that received coverage in Baptist Press and the prestigious evangelical publication Christianity Today. 

In that letter, Chinese Baptist leaders shared that women have held a vital role in the Chinese church. They noted their culture, history, and language carry a range of words for women in ministry, which include the following words: minister, teacher, evangelist, and Bible woman. 

The CBF said that because it is now the practice of some churches to give the title pastor to non-ordained church staff, any of these Chinese words may also be faithfully translated as pastor.

There are historical and cultural elements to this decision in staff titles among Chinese churches, too:

Due to persecution and a lack of mature male leaders, women played a pivotal role in evangelism, teaching, and discipleship. This still takes place today within the Chinese church in China and among the Chinese Diaspora including North America with women having shepherding roles and caring responsibilities for womens, children and youth, administrative, and other ministries under the male leadership of a senior pastor.

Like NAAF, the CBF also expressed concern over the threat of church autonomy being violated by anti-women creedalism and misunderstandings from translating Chinese words into English, yet Al Mohler would also have us believe the position, cultural heritage, language, and history of the CBF doesnt make sense.

Mohler was later asked how he would respond to the charge that what Law Amendment proponent call a more robust confessionalism (by which is meant a strict policing and shunning of churches who have women serving on staff in pastoral roles, but subordinate to a male senior pastor) could potentially violate the tried-and-true Baptist principle of local church autonomy. 

Mohler derisively and divisively replied: Okay, now that is the most ridiculous statement. Mohler then joked with the moderator, I put up with all the nonsense you said up front so far.

Al Mohlers condescending and cavalier attitude to those who have rightly expressed concern over churches acting autonomously in their hiring, staffing, and ministry decisions is beneath the dignity of his status as an entity head for several reasons, but not the least of which includes many softly complementarian churches with female pastors under the authority of male senior pastors who are in alignment with the BF&M as adopted in 2000 giving portions of tithes to the Cooperative Program from the hard-earned money of their congregants. Dr. Mohler would do well to remember it is not advisable to disenfranchise or dismiss large sections of his institutions constituency.

Many in SBC life have begun to sound the alarm over an increasingly encroaching threat of creedalism that threatens the autonomy of local churches. Two highly esteemed Southern Baptist professors, Dr. Malcolm Yarnell and Dr. Steve McKinion, recently expressed their worry over this very issue in an editorial for Baptist Press. Here is a relevant passage from that excellent piece:

We believe Baptists must be careful never to fall into the horrific error of state churches who wrongly imposed their confessions on others, including on Baptists. Indeed, Baptist confessionalism ceases to be Baptist when it is used as a weapon against others rather than as an invitation to consider the Good News of Jesus Christ, the great truths of His Word, and the free offer of salvation to all who will believe in and confess Him as their only Lord.

Would Dr. Mohler dare accuse these two highly intelligent men and seasoned SBC statesmen of nonsense? Would he suggest their thoughts dont make sense? I think not.

Dr. Mohlers contempt for those of us who commission women pastors in our autonomous congregations out of reverence for the Scriptures and under the leadership of the Spirit also reeks of a master-slave hierarchy that is unique to the worldview of Southern Seminary. Indeed, by his incendiary remarks, he has effectively dismissed the well-founded concerns of his minority SBC brothers and sisters, if not validated them. 

(He also did this when he refused to outright condemn the notorious Confederate sympathizer, credibly accused predator, and Conservative Resurgence architect Paul Pressler when he came on the cusp of excusing him because Pressler had many enemies.)

How, then, are we to make sense of what Al Mohler claims doesnt make sense to those in his theological tribe? How are we to make sense of his suggestion that women pastors dont make sense and that concerns raised by churches who employ them are nonsense?

I would suggest what is now abundantly clear to anyone with eyes to see that the push from hyper-complementarians to adopt the Law Amendment is nothing less than a concerted effort to cull minority and other women-empowering churches from life in the SBC.

It is true the advocates of the Law Amendment do not want women to have a place as pastors in the SBC. But the same is also true of their contempt for women who serve as children and youth directors, leaders, ministers, teachers, evangelists, and Bible women, likely because they know many of those Bible women threaten their own security and power in the SBC because they run the risk of being out-shepherded, out-preached, and out-Bibled.

If in Gods sovereignty the Law Amendment passes, I believe this would indicate honesty and transparency for the SBCs true anti-women and anti-minority convictions. The lions share of Cornerstones funds is currently distributed to missional and educational causes. The Baptist General Convention of Texas receives a monthly donation from Cornerstone Church, and a modest amount is designated for the CP while were awaiting the final vote on the Law Amendment. 

We will remain contributors to the BGCT as we fully embrace them and their respect for our autonomy, but we will no longer designate even a modest portion to the Cooperative Program if the Law Amendment succeeds. We simply do not have the bandwidth to financially support a funding program that currently has no minority serving as an entity head, nor one that restricts Chinese, African American, and even Anglo-American SBC congregations from following the dictates of their conscience, biblical convictions, and values by recognizing women can receive a pastoral gift from God in partnership with male leadership with affirmation of their gift.

The historic and current posture towards minorities and women in leadership being practiced and canonized in the constitution by virtue of the Law Amendment would be a bridge too far for me to cross. However, if there is a redeeming virtue to the potential passing of the Law amendment, it would be, again, the honesty, transparency, and definitive position it representsone our church would find restrictive, harmful, and unbiblical. 

Should the amendment pass, my sole regret would be the obfuscation in which the architects of the Conservative Resurgence engaged when they had the opportunity to be transparent when the BF&M was revised in 2000. 

Now, churches, women, and minorities will clearly know if they belong in the SBC who dont believe the Law Amendment should be a litmus test of orthodoxy.

Requests from my African American brothers and others who disagree with the Law Amendment to remain in the SBC until this matter reached resolution, is why I have remained thus far. My belief systems and Mohlers belief systems on this matter are irreconcilable. The only difference is, I am not trying to force him out if he does not conform to my viewpoints. But he wants me out if I dont conform to his viewpoints. As is often said in the African American community, make it make sense.

Like it or not, the Western thesis of political liberalism as a condition for successful innovation is collapsing in the face of the facts. 

Jennifer Lind, an American scholar of international relations, has courageously challenged the dominant liberal view in the West that China cannot innovate because of the "authoritarian" nature of its political system ("authoritarian" is a word that Western pundits like to use indiscriminately to refer to political systems that do not follow and/or submit to their Western liberal doxa). This Western liberal theory suggests that China will be unable to escape the "middle-income trap" or catch up with the United States economically or militarily.

Yet this view is increasingly refuted by evidence that China has risen in the global innovation ranks. Professor Lind explains China's growing innovation by the fact that the Chinese government is now pursuing policies that encourage innovation. This is an obvious reality for all of us who have been here on the ground in China over the last decade with our eyes and ears wide open. I agree with Professor Lind that, as she says, China's success in innovation has profound implications for the global balance of power.

Now, the contemporary Western liberal view that necessarily links innovation to the liberal political regime was anyway already complete nonsense to anyone who has studied history. As if humanity's innovation had only begun because of the rise of Western liberalism in the second half of the eighteenth century. As if the English Industrial Revolution had no predecessor. 

Well, in fact, it had many precursors, well before the birth of Western liberalism. Take the fourteenth-century innovation revolution in northern Italy that enabled the Renaissance for example. If some degree of liberalism appeared back then, it was not as a cause but rather as a consequence of innovation and economic expansion!

And coming back to China, another American academic, Chinese economic history expert late Robert Hartwell, demonstrated that China experienced an innovation revolution during the Song Dynasty that resulted in a phenomenal industrial revolution... long before the English Industrial Revolution. Lets emphasize that The Song Dynasty was not governed by liberal institutions or anything close to Western liberal democracy, far from it.

Therefore, it is time for Western liberal intellectuals to break out of their ideological solipsism and focus on the facts in order to describe rather than distort the world's reality.

2024 will be remembered as a year of infamy and disgrace in the otherwise unblemished international relations history of Ethiopia.

This signing occurred with flagrant disregard for international charters and treaties governing relations between sovereign nations, demonstrating Abiy Ahmed's apparent disregard for the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Republic of Somalia.
 The Republic of Somalia vehemently condemned this brazen act by the Abiy regime, and the entire international community, without exception, endorsed Somalia's position.
 Ambiguities within the terms of the MOU, coupled with deceptive motives attributed to Abiy Ahmed, a lack of support from the Ethiopian public, a no-nonsense reaction by the Republic of Somalia, the subsequent disapproval of the international community, and the rejection of the agreement by the people of Somaliland and its parliament led to the effective nullification of the MOU. This information reached President  Hassan Sheikh Mohamud of Somalia before his trip to Ethiopia to attend the 37th AU Summit of African Heads of State.

Zomato's Expansion into Blinkit and Direct-to-Consumer Space!
1. Zomato's Expansion Plans:
   - Zomato plans to expand its 10-minute delivery platform, Blinkit.
   - It aims to add products from various categories.
2. Competing with E-commerce Giants:
   - Zomato's move puts it in direct competition with Amazon and Flipkart.
3. Building Supply Chain:
   - Zomato intends to build its supply chain to directly source products and manage stock.
4. Long-term Growth Driver:
   - The push into the direct-to-consumer (D2C) space is seen as a long-term growth driver.
5. Managing Product Flow:
   - Zomato plans to manage the flow of products for D2C brands, similar to marketplaces, without owning inventory directly.
6. Attempted Acquisition:
   - Zomato attempted to acquire and merge with e-commerce enabler Shiprocket at least twice but was declined.
7. Financial Performance:
   - Blinkit's gross order value (GOV) doubled to Rs 3,542 crore in Q3FY24, with a growth of 103% YoY.
   - Revenue from ads increased by 220% YoY during Q3FY24.
   - Zomato reported a net profit of Rs 138 crore and revenue of Rs 3,288 crore for October-December.
   - This marks the third consecutive quarter of positive earnings for Zomato.
8. CEO's Statement:
   - Zomato CEO Deepinder Goyal believes Blinkit will be more valuable than the core business in the next decade.
   - Blinkit's GOV is close to Zomato's in some large cities, indicating its potential for shareholder value.

This expansion strategy into Blinkit and the D2C space reflects Zomato's efforts to diversify its business and tap into new revenue streams beyond its core food delivery service.

Three Conclusions to Improve Your Results with LLMs

I recently read the paper Financial Statement Analysis with Large Language Models, which states that the GPT-4 model, using the technique of structured prompts (Chain-of-Thought, or CoT), outperforms human financial analysts. According to the study, human precision is at 53%, while the LLM with CoT achieves 60%. The task was to analyze financial data and forecast whether a company would have profits or losses. Theres a lot to discuss about the study conducted by three affiliates from the University of Chicago Booth School of Business. This paper prompted me to delve deeper into why proper prompt engineering with Chain-of-Thought (CoT) is crucial, especially at this stage of AI development. After reading other papers, I identified three conclusions that can enhance your prompts.

First: Chain-of-Thought (CoT) is not a silver bullet

The paper Measuring Faithfulness in CoT Reasoning highlighted the inconsistent efficacy and fidelity of CoT reasoning, concluding that CoT is not universally superior to common prompts. Simply providing a structured prompt to ChatGPT will not necessarily yield better results than a conventional prompt. Without specific techniques, the results can vary significantly. Although the financial study did not share the exact prompts used, it mentioned techniques related to the following conclusions.

Second: Confirm the prompt contextualization (Inferential Bridging method)

Reading the paper Towards Faithful CoT with Inferential Bridging, despite its intimidating title, reveals that you need to provide hints of important information that the prompt should remember to reduce the risks of deviations or hallucinations.

Third: Calibrate the reasoning of your structured prompt

The paper Calibrating Reasoning in Language Models with Internal Consistency completes the puzzle on how to properly write well-structured and functional prompts using the CoT concept. The document extensively discusses how you should test each step of your prompt and calibrate it accordingly. While it may seem obvious, the normal practice is to run everything and check the results. The step-by-step compensatory system proves effective in checking the mechanics of your prompt.

I know it might sound complex, but here are three basic techniques on how to build an effective prompt:

- Procedural Approach: If you dont use a procedural approach, theres no guarantee that your highly structured prompt will be better than a normal one.

- Step-by-Step Testing: Test each step of your prompt before you just push an extensive prompt with several steps using CoT.

- Reinforce and Calibrate: During testing, you might need to reinforce important pieces of information or calibrate what is most important at each step.

If youre interested in exploring the studies further, here are the arXiv numbers:

1. Financial Statement Analysis with Large Language Models
 arXiv: 2405.18711v1
2. Measuring Faithfulness in Chain-of-Thought Reasoning
 arXiv: 2305.14388
3. Towards Faithful Chain-of-Thought: Large Language Models are Bridging Reasoners
 arXiv: 2405.18915v1
4. Calibrating Reasoning in Language Models with Internal Consistency
 arXiv: 2405.18915v1

I'm curious about records/protocols related to chain of custody and testing of samples including device calibration.

I gather athletes are expected to adhere *very* precisely to *very* strict anti-doping rules/protocols, lest they face serious repercussions: including providing detailed whereabouts, not missing tests, plus the inverted burden of proof -- if any banned substance is found in their sample, the athlete is guilty until proven innocent, etc.

I wonder if the doping/testing officials are also held to precise standards? And who monitors compliance? Who watches the watchers?

In the Valieva/Tutberitze case, the chain of custody/communication protocol of the sample seems murky. Supposedly the sample wasn't properly noted as "expedited" for an Olympian. And no one seems quite sure exactly when or how or to whom the lab results were first recorded or reported.

Shouldn't there be a detailed protocol/chain of custody document/record available for each sample which details the exact timeline of events for that sample? Including confirming correct testing device calibration?

These protocols probablly don't need to be default public, but in the case of a trail, they should def be available, and part of the trial record.

I worry a bit about athletes' rights in the sense that it seems athletes are held to very strict standards wrt doping/testing. Then they hand over a sample -- for which a positive test result could have devastating consequences for their entire career and livelihood. It seems like the doping officials then essentially say "trust us". Athletes deserve better.

Hello everyone... just want to share...a person I do not know, a person who is not followed by me, and is a person who just wants to disrupt threads or conversations about golf is listed below. As most everyone here knows me... and knows that being in the US Military from 1986 through 2016. I was not stationed in San Antonio,  Houston, or even in the United States from 2010 through early 2016. 

Remember:
In January, the Taliban struck a deal to open an office in Qatar, a move toward peace talks that the United States saw as a crucial part of a political settlement to ensure a stable Afghanistan. But two months later, the Taliban suspended preliminary talks, accusing Washington of reneging on promises to take meaningful steps toward a prisoner swap. In February, U.S. Defense Secretary Leon Panetta announces the Pentagons plan to conclude combat missions by as early as mid-2013 and shift to a primary security assistance role in Afghanistan. Meanwhile, several incidents served as blows to the international intelligence mission, I was deployed on.  Then an accidental burning of Qurans by U.S. troops and allegations that a U.S. soldier murdered at least sixteen Afghan villagers. Afghan President Karzai demanded that foreign troops be withdrawn from village outposts and confined to military bases, which analysts said would greatly accelerate the pace of transition from NATO to Afghan control. We had no internet connections, for smartphones, and even today Afghanistan's internet penetration rate stands at 18.4 percent of the total population at the start of 2023. Kepios analysis indicates that internet users in Afghanistan increased by 202 thousand (+2.7 percent) between 2022 and 2023.
Then, President Obama announces a timetable for withdrawing most U.S. forces from Afghanistan by the end of 2016. The first phase of his plan calls for 9,800 U.S. troops to remain after the combat mission concludes at the end of 2014, limited to training Afghan forces in intelligence and conducting operations against the remnants of al-Qaeda.

I don't live in a cold climate and can golf all year round so I've been learning a lot from my students over the past 12-18 months

I can imagine how much the mind wonders when working on your golf inside, into a net, in a simulator etc...

I can imagine it's soooo easy to jump online and try the next best "tip" you saw online... 

I can imagine it's hard to stick with that "One Thing" your coach gave you...

If you are a keen golfer who has a lot of time on your hands to hit balls, this game must be super difficult to not just try stuff and not commit to one thing...

But you need to try. This is why when you are inside, stick with practicing in 15 min intervals... that way, you don't have time to get off task.

'Ice Legend' takes China-Russia friendship to new heights
More than 10 Russian figure skaters, some of whom are former world champions and Olympic medalists, provided a visual feast for Chinese sports fans at "Ice Legend: World Champion Show 2024," a two-day tour performance held at the Capital Indoor Stadium in Beijing during this year's Spring Festival. In this edition of the Hub, Wang Guan talks to Evgenia Medvedeva, a two-time gold medalist at the World Figure Skating Championships, and to Elizaveta Tuktamysheva, the 2015 world champion, to discuss the show's significance two years after the Beijing Winter Olympics and asks them how it feels to reconnect with the Chinese audience. Wang also talks to Victoria Sinitsina and Nikita Katsalapov, the pair winners of the silver medal in the ice-dancing event at the Beijing Winter Olympics, who provided a stunning performance at the venue. "China is a signature place for us," they say, as Wang asks them about the warm reception they always get from their fans whenever they perform in China. And Tatiana Volosozhar, the 2013 Figure Skating World Champion, tells Wang how important the China-Russia Year of Sports Exchanges is for nurturing figure skating talents and learning from each other's skills. Also, Wang learns how to jump and spin under the guidance of Tuktamysheva.

CBN started with a Fixed Exchange Rate: Exchange rate managed by the Central Bank. Rate is fixed in relation to another currency

When the central bank INCREASES the exchange ($1:400 to $1: 600) it's a devaluation, opposite is a revaluation

(figures are examples)

Then CBN moved to a managed float (or dirty float) in a dirty float the currency is allowed to freely float but the central bank intervenes to keep it within a bank

So the CBN can say if Naira falls to $1:700, CBN will sell $ To BDC and buy Naira, thus forcing the exchange rate back to $1:N600

To maintain a fixed rate or even a managed float, you need reserves

The CBN reserves are not yet buoyant so it has introduced administrative actions to prop up the value of the naira e.g. Not allowing full repatriation of oil proceeds immediately 

All currencies are defended, the Swiss Franc is freely floated, and it's also convertible but the Swiss central bank intervenes in the open market to buy and sell currency to appreciate or depreciate the exchange rate of the Swiss franc

So in summary 

A pegged currency gives control but Is expensive, most gulf oil states peg their currency to the dollar 

A managed float is a hybrid between a freely floating currency and full peg. Central bank allows the currency to float but within guardrails 

A full float means the market sets exchange rates via price discovery but the Central Bank can intervene not by pegs but by buying and selling local or foreign currency on the free market to affect the exchange rate

(FYI) Phil talks about Layoffs and the Industry Slowdown

- Microsoft laid off around 1,900 workers from a gaming group in January.

- The global video game industry is growing but barely, with 2023 game industry revenues up only 0.6% from 2022.

- Microsoft is struggling to find new players, with console games playing a significant portion of the market.

- I don't think we're doing a good enough job finding new players, Spencer said. Let's pick consoles as a good example: We found 200 million global households that will play console games. And that number really hasn't changed in the last five, six years.

- We've raised the price of games, he added, acknowledging the increasingly common $70 price point following nearly two decades of $60 games. We went through COVID. We found ways of getting more money per player. I think at some point you reach a peak on that, and, frankly, it can go to some places that are manipulative that I'm not a big fan of.

- The solution is to find new customers, and you find new customers through new ways of delivering games to players who can't play those games today, whether that's device, whether that's access, whether that's price point of video games.

- I have a commitment to the company on the Xbox business being a profitable and growing part of Microsoft, he said. And I need to put us in the best position for long-term growth. Most of that is about building great products that exceed their expectations and find millions of customers. But honestly, you know, the cost of building the products inclusive of the people who work on themI need to make sure we have enough of the right people and the right number of people in the right places for us to succeed.

Over 4.1 million BTC have not moved in at least 7 years.

Think about that.

If you bought 8 years ago and moved your coins to a new hardware wallet 4 years ago, I'm not talking about those coins. Coins that have been dormant on the blockchain for over 7 years.

Put differently, almost 21% of the circulating supply has not moved to change hardware wallets, addresses, be sold, etc. in over 7 years.

Likely most of these coins are lost forever.

When you factor in lost coins that are younger than 7 years, it's feasible to estimate that around 5 million BTC (or more) are lost.

As Satoshi Nakamoto said, Lost coins only make everyone elses coins worth slightly more. Think of it as a donation to everyone.

The supply cap for Bitcoin is 21 million but the actual circulating, in use supply, may only be 13-15 million over the next century as you factor in lost coins.

PROTEIN DESIGN TRANSFORM BIOTECHNOLOGY VIA AI AND ML

In recent years, artificial intelligence (AI) has become a key player in advancing biotechnology and medicine. The fusion of AI with protein design is paving the way for groundbreaking developments, from new vaccines to enzymes designed from scratch.

Three years after the AlphaFold2 discovery, AIs potential in protein design is more apparent than ever. The technology has led to the creation of new proteins, antibodies, enzymes, and vaccines. By using advanced AI models, scientists are unlocking new possibilities for drug development and biotechnology, marking a significant leap in the field.

Machine learning, a subset of AI, is redefining the world of protein design. It accelerates the creation of proteins for medical and biotechnological use. By applying machine learning, researchers can now engineer proteins with enhanced functions, paving the way for innovative treatments and solutions.

Predicting protein functions with AI
An innovative AI tool, DeepGO-SE, has emerged as a game-changer in predicting the functions of unknown proteins. This tool stands out by analyzing proteins without clear matches, using logical principles to infer functions. DeepGO-SEs ability to explore proteins in extreme environments opens new doors for biotechnological research.

Meta AIs research into evolutionary scale modeling (ESM) represents a bold step towards creating proteins that do not exist in nature. This approach uses language models to predict protein structures, pushing the boundaries of protein design and folding. Despite challenges, this research highlights  the commitment to advancing the field.

Machine learning models play a crucial role in protein design, categorized into sequence-based, sequence-label, and structure-based models. These models enable scientists to design new proteins and optimize their structures, which is crucial for drug discovery and medical research.

Practical applications and tools
DIProT, an interactive protein design toolkit, exemplifies the practical application of AI in solving the protein inverse folding problem. By leveraging deep learning, DIProT demonstrates competitive performance, showcasing the potential of AI in revolutionizing protein design.

The announcement of AlphaFold2 marked a turning point in computational methods for predicting protein structure from sequence data. This milestone, combined with advances in AI, signals a shift in protein design. The industry anticipates an AlphaFold moment for functional protein engineering, aiming to create functional proteins on demand.

The future of protein design
The integration of AI with protein design is set to transform biotechnology and medicine significantly. The ability to design proteins from scratch heralds a new era of possibilities in drug development, enzyme design, and vaccine creation. As this field advances, the promise of AI and protein design continues to offer new solutions and hope for the future of global health.

Artificial intelligence is not just a tool but a catalyst for innovation in biotechnology and medicine. By advancing protein design, AI opens up unprecedented possibilities for the development of new treatments and solutions. As the field continues to grow, the synergy between AI and protein design promises to lead the way in transforming healthcare and biotechnology.

Located in Madison, WI.  Promega is a based manufacturer of enzymes and other products for biotechnology and molecular biology with a portfolio covering the fields of genomics, protein analysis and expression, cellular analysis, drug discovery, and genetic identity.

The company now offers more than 4,000 life science products used by scientists, researchers and life science and pharmaceutical companies. Promega has 1,601 employees. Revenue is approaching $450 million (USD) in 2019.

The privately held company has branch offices in 16 countries and more than 50 global distributors serving 100 countries. 

Promega Corporation also established the first biotechnology joint venture in China (Sino-American Biotechnology Co. in 1985)

The company's portfolio began with products for genomics researchers and now includes cloning systems, luciferase reporters, and amplification products as well as the original restriction and modifying enzymes. The portfolio of amplification products includes the GoTaq family of polymerases, buffers and the Plexor quantitative PCR system.

Along with Applied Biosystems, Promega participated with the FBI and other crime labs in validating STR loci that would eventually be selected as the core loci for the Combined DNA Index System (CODIS), used for forensic DNA testing in North America.

One of my favorite thought experiments paraphrased from Alan Watts to fit current technological climate: 

If you could submerse yourself into a full sensory virtual reality and live any sort of life with no limit -  at first we would be rich, we'd be kings, queens, superheroes. Live out fantastic space operas, rom-coms, meet our soulmates, immerse ourselves into all pleasurable experiences our mind could imagine. 
After a while, experiences filled with only pleasure would get a bit boring, you'd want to switch it up. Dive into some experiences laced with drama. Experiences that provoke danger, excitement. Experience that make you say "whew that was a close one, wasn't it?". You go into games like Call of Duty, Cyberpunk, GTA, movies like Mission Impossible, Avengers. Dramatic movies, maybe even thrillers. Experiences where you have to put effort into them to win. 
But there would still be the knowing you were in a game, that you weren't really playing like your life depended on it. 
Eventually you'd want a bit of randomness, to roll the dice. 
You'd start having experiences where you allow yourself to forget you're in VR. To increase the steaks, to increase the immersion. 
You'd roll the dice much more, let randomness of circumstance play a part in your experience. 
Eventually, with enough rolls of those dice, you'd end up where you are right now, in this very moment, in this very life.

I like this experiment because it let's me play into the idea that this life I'm living now, with all its wonders and hardships - might be the very thing a being with infinite amounts of power at their fingertips want to experience. Immersion. Pleasure. Pain. Heartbreak. Love. Fear. Hope. Not knowing who, or where I am. Just being. A god's dream.

WHAT IS DIFFERENT ABOUT NEURAL NETS?
DECISION MAKING!
I fly an airplane (B787) with a very sophisticated auto flight system (autopilot/autothrottles).  But the system is NOT SMART.  

CODED DECISIONS
Every decision is a line of code.  

No line of code?  It shuts itself off or operates in a degraded code. 

Situation unfamiliar to the plane?  Either shuts itself off, or worse, does the exact wrong thing.

VS INFERENCE COMPUTE
Teslas FSD is SMART.  Neural nets add inference to the AV solution.  The car can figure out what to do because it has seen something similar before.  There doesnt have to be a cell connection (no cars getting stranded because cells towers are jammed).  There doesnt have to be a human intervening every few miles (Cruise).

Newbie Observations of Tesla Autopilot

Greetings! Most of what we hear on  about Teslas driving themselves is Full Self Driving (FSD) Beta, but I thought Id share a few thoughts from someone new to the Tesla environment who only has Autopilot (names I dont like, but I already put that in a post).

Having driven a Tesla just under 2 weeks now, I have experimented a few times with Autopilot and here are some observations:

1. It does what it does very well - it follows the lanes, stays in traffic and controls speed well.
2. This feature would be excellent on a long highway drive.
3. You need to remember that it does NOT change lanes (unless you have Advanced Autopilot).
4. If you manually change lanes, it appears that overrides the Autosteer functionality, but does not disable Traffic Aware Cruise Control.
5. It seems like the way to turn off Traffic Aware Cruise Control is to tap the regular brake. My opinion, this transition is awkward and can be dangerous if misunderstood.

I suspect many of the issues that have been reported over time with Teslas behaving badly (running into stopped vehicles, etc) were likely related to people trying to use 1 pedal driving after they had engaged Traffic Aware Cruise Control and the car did not slow down when they expected it to.

I say this because I love 1 pedal driving and remembering to hit that brake pedal to regain control of speed after a TACC session is not at all intuitive. I have not been close to hitting anything, but definitely had to figure out how to slow down a few times.

Just a few thoughts from a newbie here. Please correct anything I got wrong or add your own observations in replies!
Finally! Ive totaled two Teslas already because I couldnt handle the weird P icon. I got so distracted that I accidentally turned on autopilot which drove me off a cliff.

DRAGONS EXISTED

CONFIRMED BY ZETATALK

ZetaTalk: Dragons, written Jul 15, 1995

Mankind has many myths about dragons throughout the world. In the Orient the dragon is featured on pottery and in parades, and European myths are replete with Knights in armor going into battle against firebreathing dragons. The dragons invariable have wings and are shaped suspiciously like dinosaurs. Is there some basis in fact for this common human memory? Indeed there is. Where the dinosaurs died out long before mankind was engineered into being from ape stock, the Earth was not the only planet to give birth to such creatures. Evolution follows similar patterns, and where your Earth brought forth dinosaurs with wings, just so did other planets compatible with the Earth.

Your dragons were transplants brought to the Earth by early ambassadors from the Service-to-Self, who anticipated an increased harvest of lackeys from the Earth due to the fear and despair their dragons wrought. Were the dragons intelligent and incarnated with souls? No. On a scale of 1 to 10, where the average dog is a 10, a dragon was barely a 3. This is why, in spite of the massive size and capacity to fly as well as lumber over hill and dale, they were so easily slain. Dumb brutes. Hundreds were brought to Earth, and released on terrified villages. The dragons ate humans, which were neither swift runners or able to barricade themselves in their mud huts, and were a tastier morsel than the deer, which ran fast and had taut, lean muscles.

The legends speak of sacrifices, where humans would periodically offer one of their own to placate the dragon. Well, of course this reduced the rampages, as dinner had been brought to the door. Where some dragons mated, they were scattered to begin with and, dying without progeny, eventually disappeared from the Earth. There were perhaps a few hundred delivered, and their reign, ending only in the last Millennia, lasted for thousands of years. The stories of dragons, all the more impressive as they were true, spread more widely than the dragons themselves. Did they breathe fire? No. But when roaring, open mouthed, it felt like that to those within range. Hot breath and a big windpipe.

Here are some of the major philosophical schools that were create during this period:

Confucianism: Founded by Confucius (Kong Fuzi), this school emphasized morality, proper social relationships, justice, and sincerity. Confucianism became the dominant ideology in later Chinese history, particularly during the Han Dynasty.

Daoism (Taoism): Laozi and Zhuangzi are the most notable figures in Daoism. This philosophy advocates for a life in harmony with the Dao (Way), emphasizing naturalness, simplicity, and non-action (wu-wei).

Legalism: Focused on strict laws and harsh punishments, Legalists like Han Fei and Li Si believed that strong, authoritarian governance was the key to social order. Legalism became influential during the Qin Dynasty.

Mohism: Founded by Mozi, Mohism promoted universal love, meritocracy, and pacifism, challenging the hierarchical and ritualistic norms of Confucianism.

School of Yin-Yang and the Five Elements: This school combined cosmology and philosophy, influencing Chinese medicine, divination, and Feng Shui.

School of Names (Logicians): Philosophers like Gongsun Long and Hui Shi focused on logic, paradoxes, and the nature of language and reality.

Agrarianism: Advocated returning to an agrarian society where communal land ownership and agricultural self-sufficiency were emphasized.

Military Strategists: This group, including Sun Tzu, author of "The Art of War," focused on tactics and strategy, reflecting the era's pervasive warfare.

A ruins of street at the ancient city of Harappa (2600-1900 BC), Indus Valley Civilisation site; now in Pakistan.

Harappan architecture was very different and unique, when compared with any other civilizations of the time and shows certain elements which later civilizations of the Indian civilization borrowed from.

The architecture of the Harappan Civilization was very unique and had no foreign influences. The use of the architecture was mostly for the purpose of functions and not for beauty or decoration. The evolution of the architecture of the civilization occurs in isolation and has been influenced by the local cultures; which prevailed previously years back of the first farming and pastoralist settlements. The maturity and elegance which is present in the architecture of the Harappan civilization is unique and no other civilization can match its level of complexity and style.

The main prespective behind the architecture of Harappan Civilization is that of utilitarian. They were also one of the first to introduce separate workers quaters. The cities in Harappan civilization didnt have same town designs but most of the buildings followed a similar pattern. Most of the building structures included defensive wall, citadel and lower town, as well as alleys and roadways, drainage and water management systems. The plan of the city was created by use of geometrcial tools and followed a certain pattern, citadel being located in the west of lower town, however in some cities it was located in south. Cardinal directions of streets and lanes were used for partitioning certain rural villages to some blocks and sub-blocks and the residences were mostly lined up on both the sides of the streets. 

The streets and roadways were all straight mostly and intersected at the right angle. All roadways were constructed with burned bricks, with the lenght of each of brick being four times its height and also breadth being two times its height. The city was split into rectangular blocks by streets and also roadways. There were also evidences of trash cans.

The archaeological site of Harappa was heavily damaged under British and French rule, when bricks from the ruins were used as track ballast in the construction of the Lahore-Multan Railway. The current village of Harappa is less than 1km from the ancient site. In 2005, a controversial amusement park scheme at the site was abandoned when builders unearthed many archaeological artefacts during the early stages of building work.

The Sun Temple of Modhera is a remarkable example of ancient Hindu architecture dedicated to the solar deity Surya. It was built in the 11th century CE by the Chaulukya king Bhima I, who also defended his kingdom from the invasion of Mahmud of Ghazni. 

The temple complex consists of three parts: a rectangular water tank with 108 small shrines, a pillared assembly hall with intricate carvings of the sun god and other deities, and a sanctum sanctorum that was designed to align with the sun rays on the equinox days. 

The temple is no longer in use for worship, but it is a protected monument maintained by the Archaeological Survey of India.

Face Reconstruction of Ramses II, based on the Pharoah's Mummy.

Ramesses II (1304-1214 BC), also known as Ramesses the Great, left a profound impact on ancient Egyptian architecture and culture. 

Ramesses II commissioned numerous monumental building projects, including grand temples and colossal statues. One of the most famous examples is the Ramesseum, his mortuary temple located on the west bank of the Nile in Thebes (modern-day Luxor). The temple showcased his power and divine status, with intricate reliefs and massive statues of the pharaoh. His construction projects also extended to other cities and religious sites across Egypt.

Ramesses II is particularly renowned for his temple complex at Abu Simbel. Carved into the cliffs along the Nile, these temples were dedicated to the gods Amun-Ra, Ra-Horakhty, and Ptah, as well as to Ramesses himself. The Great Temple of Abu Simbel features four colossal statues of Ramesses II on its facade, showcasing his dominance and divine connection.

Ramesses II's reign witnessed an artistic revival characterized by intricate and detailed relief carvings. These carvings adorned the walls of temples and tombs, depicting scenes from religious rituals, military campaigns, and everyday life. The carvings often portrayed Ramesses II in a larger-than-life manner, emphasizing his authority and achievements.

Ramesses II developed a cult of personality, promoting himself as a mighty ruler and a living god. He used art, architecture, and monumental structures to enhance his image and solidify his position as a powerful deity on Earth. This cult of personality contributed to the overall cultural ethos of ancient Egypt during his reign.

Ramesses II's architectural and cultural achievements had a lasting impact on subsequent Egyptian dynasties. His building projects and artistic style influenced later pharaohs, who sought to emulate his grandeur and establish their own divine connections. The artistic and architectural legacy of Ramesses II continues to inspire and fascinate historians, archaeologists, and tourists to this day.

Ramesses II's reign marked a period of architectural and cultural flourishing in ancient Egypt, leaving behind a rich legacy that showcases the grandeur and artistic prowess of the time.

The Ides of March is a day on the Roman calendar, corresponding to March 15th. It gained notoriety as the day Julius Caesar was assassinated in 44 BC, as famously dramatized in William Shakespeare's play, "Julius Caesar." The phrase "Beware the Ides of March" is often used to warn of impending doom or misfortune.

Interestingly, the Ides of March originally had a non-threatening history. Kalends, Nones, and Ides were ancient markers used to reference dates in relation to lunar phases. Ides simply referred to the first full moon of a given month, which usually fell between the 13th and 15th. In fact, the Ides of March once signified the new year, which meant celebrations and rejoicing.

So, while the Ides of March may have a dark reputation due to Caesar's assassination, its origins are more mundane and even celebratory.
